    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <div class="card">
        <p>This comparison focuses specifically on passive, index-tracking vehicles. Actively managed ETFs and mutual funds involve different considerations regarding manager risk and significantly higher fee structures. Tax efficiency explanations assume US tax law as of 2026. Vanguard's patented structure that allowed its mutual funds to operate as a share class of its ETFs expired in 2023, allowing other issuers to theoretically adopt similar structures, though ETFs remain the standard for tax efficiency in taxable accounts.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question">What is the main difference between an ETF and an Index Fund?</div>
            <div class="faq-answer">The main difference is how they trade. ETFs trade on an exchange like a stock, meaning their price fluctuates throughout the day and you can buy/sell anytime the market is open. Index funds (structured as mutual funds) trade only once a day at the closing net asset value (NAV) price.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question">Which is more tax-efficient: an ETF or an Index Fund?</div>
            <div class="faq-answer">ETFs are generally more tax-efficient due to their unique creation and redemption mechanism, which avoids capital gains distributions. Vanguard index funds are an exception, as they held a patent allowing their mutual funds to share the tax efficiency of their ETF counterparts.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question">Can I automatically reinvest dividends with both?</div>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Most brokerages allow automatic dividend reinvestment (DRIP) for both ETFs and mutual funds. However, mutual funds natively support reinvestment into fractional shares, whereas ETF DRIP capabilities depend on your specific broker supporting fractional ETF shares.</div>
        </div>
    </div>

  
